<HEADLINE>
<P>
OPERA AS MUSIC AND AS THEATER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Times music critic Martin Bernheimer gave readers a perceptive and sensitive 
review of the commendable musical achievements of the Music Center Opera's new 
production of "Idomeneo" ("Meddling With Mozart," Sept. 27). 
</P>
<P>
The conductor, orchestra and singers gave elegant, virtuoso performances, just 
as Bernheimer reports. 
</P>
<P>
However, Bernheimer's editors did us a disservice by not also assigning a 
theater writer to review this magical new production designed by Maurice 
Sendak. Bernheimer really misses the mark in his lengthy (70% of his review) 
diatribe against the stage direction and design of the production. 
</P>
<P>
The producers of this new "Idomeneo" remember that opera is theater as well as 
music. And this production is very good theater. 
</P>
<P>
JOHN H. WELBORNE 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
