<HEADLINE>
<P>
MAPPLETHORPE EXHIBIT ENDS TOUR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BOSTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A traveling exhibit of Robert Mapplethorpe's photographs closed Friday, leaving 
in its wake protests and a conservative attack on the National Endowment for 
the Arts. 
</P>
<P>
The exhibit combined Mapplethorpe's explicit homoerotic photographs -- the main 
source of the controversy -- with cool, elegant portraits and photographs of 
flowers. 
</P>
<P>
Mapplethorpe helped organize the show shortly before he died of AIDS in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
Boston was the last stop on the exhibit's seven-city tour. About 103,000 people 
saw the show during its nine weeks at the Institute of Contemporary Art, about 
twice the number that visited the museum all last year, said Arthur Cohen, 
director of marketing. 
</P>
<P>
Controversy over the exhibit forced the national endowment's new director, John 
E. Frohnmayer, to institute a requirement that artists sign a statement 
agreeing to not use NEA funds to make obscene art. Some have turned down grants 
in protest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
